thus\nfar to 1930 were 22.7 per' cent tower\nthan to the corresponding period ot last\nyear, according to a compilation by\nMoody\u2019s Investors Service. The in\ndustrial group alone, comprising 236\ncompanies, showed an average loss of\n31.8 per cent for the first nine months,\nand a third quarter drop of 47.9 per\ncent as compared to 1929 results.\nThe analysis comments on the fact\nthat, despite the general downward\ntrend, 29 of the industrials (or 12.3\nper cent of the total) Were able to re\nport higher third quarter earnings than\nin 1929, while 41 companies, represent\ning 17.4 per cent of the industrial\nclassification, had larger profits during\nthe first nine months than in the cor\nresponding period of last year.\nThe combined total was aided by an\naverage gain of 4.4 per cent in earn\nings of 95 light, power, gas and traction\ncompaines during the first eight months\nof the year. September figures for this\ngroup not having jfet been reported.\nOnly 2 Industrial groups out of a\ntotal of 29 recorded gains in the nine\nmonth period, Moody\u2019s states. \"Four\namusement companies had a composite\nearnings advance of 32.5 per cent,\nwhile six railroad equipment corpora\ntions showed a profit increase of 13.2\nper cent.\n\"Greatest percentage declines were\nsuffered by automobiles, excluding Gen\neral Motors, which lost 72.3 per cent:\ncoal (57.5 per cent), copper (06.1 per\ncent), the miscellaneous non-ferrous\nmetal group (65.9 per cent) and tex\ntiles (43 per cent).\n\"Cement, food products, paper and\npublishing and printing companies all\nreported nine-month earnings that were\nonly slightly below those of last year.\u201d\nThe review adds that earnings pros\npects for the final quarter exhibit lit\ntle hope of improvement to most classi\nfications, but that comparisons with\npreceding year\u2019s earnings should be\ncome increasingly favorable from now on.\nGoodyear Tire 4b Bubber.\nNEW YORK. November 8 (A*).\u2014Dow,\nJones A Co. says that, regsrdiess of\nlower earnings, it Is the present Inten\ntion of the Board of Directors of the\nGoodyear Tire Rubber Co. to pay\nthe regular dividend on the common\nstock for at least the next two quar\nters. The regular quarterly dividend\non the common is *1.25.\nNEW YORK BANK STOCKS\nNEW YORK. November 8 (VP).\u2014Over\nthe-counter market.\nm*m I?\nfbaLpfonix '.V.V.'.V.V\u2019.7.'V.' g\nPeoples National 350\nj\n\nBUY NOW\nfor\nBETTER BUSINESS\nPromote Purchasing Power\nIf every homeowner, store proprietor and business firm manager will inventory his odd Jobs\nof replacement, renewal and repair enough work will be discovered to give immediate employ*\nment to every unemployed man and woman in Washington.\nThis step would increase at once the purchasing power of persons now' unemployed. More\nmoney would be put into circulation, business operations would be speeded up and locdl firms\nwould have to hire more employes to handle the resulting increase in business.\nYou can promote community purchasing power and hasten business revival by digging Up\n!ong>deferred jobs of cleaning, redecoration, remodeling and repair and by giving such jobs\nto unemployed persons now willing and waitin g for work.\nEach new job which you create helps some worthy person back on the road to self*suppOrt. He\nthen joins with you in the army of buyers whose united purchases are the only sure means of\nrecreating confidence.\nCalvin Coolidge states, \u201cIt is a public duty to buy what you can afford.\u201d Create a Hew job and\nenable others to join with you to \"Buy Now for Better Business\u201d\nh\nWashington \u201cBUY NOW Committe*\nBISHOP WILLIAM F. McDOWELL, of MARK LANBBURGH. President. Mer- JAMES B. EDMUNDS, President,\nthe Method let Episcopal Church chants Sc Manufacturers Assocla- Klwanis Club.\n(South). tlon. DR. atnr yt. LEADBETTER, President,\nBISHOP JAMES E. FREEMAN, of the SIDNEY B LUST, President, Motion Lions Club.\nEpiscopal Church. Picture Theater Owners of Wash- WILLIAM 