\nday\u2019s steadiness. Spots were advanced\n20 points to 11.15.\nCotton range:\nOpen. High Low. Close.\nDecember, old Tl-if 1f.50 11.14\njwu^y. c 'ofd w 11$ H:2\u00b07 l!:\u00a7\n*K ry :.r r 11:3 M sis\n3\u00ae ill ll:J\u00bb \\m\nOctober 11.93 12 23 11.99 12.12\nGRAIN MARKET\nCHICAGO, November 8 (Special).\u2014\nThe wheat market was steady today at\nthe staff, but weakened a few minutes\nlater under scattered liquidation. De\ncember old, opened 74*4 to 74%: new,\n743/\u201e; March, old, 78% to IB 1 May, I\nold, 80Vo to 80%; new, 80Vi to 80\nAfter the first half hour, December, old,\n74V*; new. 74V/4; March, old, 78 4 May,\nold and new, Bd%.\nCorn followed the action of wheat.\nDecember, old, opened 73% to 73% i\nnew. 733/*; March, old, 78%; new, 76%:\nMay. old, 78%; new 78%. After the\nfirst hall hour, December, old, 73%:\nnew, 7 33/ 4 March, old, 76%; new, 76%;\nMay old, 78%; new, 78%.\nOats were quiet and easier. Decem\nber old. opened 32; March, old, 34%;\nMay. old, 35% to 35'%; new, 35%. Af\nter the first half hour, December old,\n32; March, Old, 34; May, old, 33>/ a\nnew, 35%.\nProvisions were firm.\nAmerican Cyanamid Co.\nNEW YORK, November 8 (JP)< \u2014The\nAmerican Cyadamid Co. is reported ne\ngotiating for acquisition of A. Klip\nstato A Co., chemical manufacturers\nand importers,\nFINANCIAL,\nBALTIMORE BUSINESS\nIN FAVORABLE POSITION\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE. November B.\u2014There\nare indications that buaineaa in Balti\nmore was making a fairly favorable\ncomparison with last year during (he\nmonth Just closed. Debits to Indi\nvidual accounts, or check transactions\nat the local banks, ad reported by the\nclearing house, totaled 8408,657,842 for\nOctober, oomparad with $417,341,948\nfor the same month last year, thus\nshowing only a moderate decline under\nthe level of a year ago.\nBank clearings for October totaled\n3423.888489. against $491,179,983 for\nthe same month last year. For the 10\nmonths the total was $4,030,805,200,\ncompared with $4,413,772,213.\nAUSTRALIAN WHEAT CROP.\nCANBERRA, Australia, November 8\nf/P).\u2014The commonwealth government\ni statistician estimates the Australian\nwheat crop will total 215,000.000 bush\nels this crop year.\nThe estimates by states are as fol\nlows: New South Wales. 72,000,000\nbushels; Victoria, 55.500,000; Queens\nland, 4,500,000; South Australia, 33,-\n000,000; West Austria, 49,600,000, and\nTasmania, 500,000.\nThe commonwealth\u2019s wheat produc\ntion is steadily mounting, the present\nestimates being practically d wMe the\nyield of two years ago.\nDUN'S PRICE INDEX LOWER.\nMonthly comparison* of Dun's index\nnumber of whosesale commodity prices,\nproportioned to consumption, follow;\nNov. l, oct. l, Nov. i,\nGroups. 1930. 1930 1639\nBrtadstufts $37,349 130.994 $34,878\nMeat 18.884 18.884 38.110\nDairy and garden 20.323 20 190 32-657\nMliSr f00d....... 17.880 IT.tti 18.690\nCidthin* i 38.109 38.487 14.888\n\\lt\u00bbceflaneoui'! 33.324 33 788 Jill!\nTotal 1185.188 SIBB 309 $191.178\nA-15\nSEASONAL UPTURN\nIN CANADA TRADE\n\nTextiles Better\u2014Gain in Em\nployment\u2014Weather Puts\nDamper on Threshing.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tha Star.\nMONTREAL, November B.\u2014The sea\nsonal increase in Canadian business\nwhich sat in a month ago has lifted the\ngeneral economic trend somewhat above\nthe low level of the preceding months,\naccording to general manager 8. H\nLogan of the Canadian Bank of Com\nmerce in a discussion of current Ca\nnadian business and agricultural con\nditions. The increase is moat noticeable\nin textiles and footwear, and some of\nthe so-called \u2018heavy\" industries are\nslightly more active, but Mr. Logan\npoints out that the purchasing power of\nthe farming communities Is being built\nup on the weakest foundation In many\nyears. Logging and lumbering are at a\nlow abb. Base metal mining la unable\nto keep up the pace set earlier in the\nyear. Construction contracts have de\nclined to the extent that the value of\nwork in progress is 28 per cent less than\nat this time a year ago.\n\"Offsetting factors,\u201d Mr Logan adds,\n\"\u25a0-o the seasonal increase in soma\ntrades, which may be expected to con\ntinue for another two months; the\nmeasures undertaken to afford unem\nployment relief in the form of public\nworks and advanced projects by the\nrailroads, an improvement in the ex\nport wheat trade, an expansion in coal\nmining in the Western fields, such as\noccurs at this period every year, and a\ngrowing Interest by American and\nBritish manufacturers in the Canadian\ntrade field, which is reflected in the es\ntablishment of branch factories, par\nticularly by the Americans.\n\"It is cold comfort,\" continues Mr\nLogan, \"but it is a fact that there has\nbeen less cause for concern in Canada\nthan in many other parts of the world.\nThe decline in Canadian industry, es\npecially manufacturing, during the third\nquarter is now seen to have been more\nsevere than during the first half.\u201d\nConcerning agricultural conditions.\nMr. Logan says: \u201cBad weather has vir\ntually suspended threshing operations\nin western Canada and adversely af\nfected the grades of some wheat. In ad\ndition to this, Die more extensive use of\ngrains this year for feed on the farms\nand local milling indicates that the\ncrop for market will be below normal.\nFruit crops, however, have turned out\nsomewhat larger than forecast.\"\nRail Traffic Gains.\nNEW YORK. November 8 O*V\u2014T. E\nWilliamson, president of the Chlcegc.\nBurlington Quincy Railroad, aald that\ntraffic over the system during the first\ndays of November showed a slight in\ncrease over like days of last year and\nthat \"while the showing la not much to\nbrag about. It might indicate a slight\nupturn.\" The increase in loadings for\nthe first four days this month was about\n1.5 per cent over last year, the added\ntraffic being largely In grain, fruits and\nvegetables and some of the hegvier com\nmodities.\nWOOLWORTH SALES.\nNEW YORK, November 8 W.\nWoolworth Co. reported October sales\nof $20,421,522, a decrease or 4.5 per\ncent from $27,878,313 for the corre\nsponding month last year Pbr the first\n10 months this year salts totaled $222,*\n889,381, a decrease of 4.2 per cent from\n$239,720,022 for the like period of 192*.\nH. T. Parson, president, said that Oc\ntober sales showed an increase of It\nper cent over the $21552,634 repented\nfor September. He added that live dis\ntricts showed a gain in sales tn Oc\ntober over 1929.","height":"25470","width":"19791"}}
